<section class="guidelines landing-guide" id="guidelines">
  <div class="help-header"><h2>Bandwidth Calculator Guide</h2><p>Why the math is trickier than it looks, and how to use the 3 modes.</p></div>
  <div class="help-grid">
    <div class="help-card"><h3>The bits-vs-bytes trap</h3><ul><li>File sizes are in <strong>bytes</strong> (KB, MB, GB, TB). 1 byte = 8 bits.</li><li>Connection speeds are in <strong>bits</strong> per second (Kbps, Mbps, Gbps). Always lowercase "b".</li><li>To convert: <em>seconds = (size_in_MB &times; 8) / speed_in_Mbps</em></li><li>Example: 100&nbsp;MB on 100&nbsp;Mbps = 800 megabits / 100 Mbps = 8 seconds. Not 1 second.</li><li>This calculator does the conversion for you &mdash; you never have to multiply by 8 manually.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>3 solve modes</h3><ul><li><strong>Transfer time</strong>: size + speed -> how long it takes.</li><li><strong>File size</strong>: speed + available time -> how much you can move.</li><li><strong>Required speed</strong>: size + deadline -> what link speed you need.</li><li>Click the tab at the top of the tool to switch modes.</li><li>Presets at the bottom pre-fill the speed field for common link types.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Real-world vs theoretical</h3><ul><li>This calculator reports <strong>100% efficient</strong> transfer. Reality is 85-95%.</li><li>Overhead sources: TCP/IP headers, TLS handshake, HTTP framing, slow-start, retransmits, server-side processing.</li><li>Practical rule of thumb: multiply the calculator's time by 1.15 for realistic estimates.</li><li>LAN transfers (SMB, NFS) can hit 95-98% of line rate. WAN transfers over VPN are often 50-70% due to encryption overhead.</li></ul></div>
    <div class="help-card"><h3>Storage units (KiB vs KB)</h3><ul><li>This calculator uses <strong>binary KB</strong> (1 KB = 1024 bytes) because that is what Windows and most file managers display.</li><li>Disk manufacturers use <strong>decimal</strong> (1 MB = 1,000,000 bytes), which is why a "1 TB drive" shows as ~931 GB in Windows.</li><li>Binary is <em>KiB/MiB/GiB</em> in strict standards; decimal is <em>kB/MB/GB</em>. Most users say "MB" meaning binary, so the calculator follows that convention.</li><li>The difference is ~7% at the GB level, ~10% at the TB level.</li></ul></div>
  </div>
